text: To all those who will be complaining about another Cinderella film...  You definitely don't know how Hollywood works, do you? It's a big financial gamble if the studios were to invest in something new. If a producer or director were to approach the studios with an original story, then they, along with many other people, are at risk of losing their job. Why do you think a lot of studios are now taking the safe route by spawning out remakes and reboots? They know that people who are familiar with these stories will pay to see it. It's show business. Besides, there have been a large number of original films out there, but they're either unheard of, or they didn't do so well. Quit your complaining and stop falling into the category of a "whinger".

text: To be honest, I kinda like this. Cinderella is a classic in film-making and animation, and although some would argue that you cannot replicate the timeless film, I believe a live-action version would not retract from the film, but almost deliver the Cinderella story to today's generation of children. I'm intrigued by this film and what it may offer. Disney has been making many live action films like Alice in Wonderland and Maleficent, and they have not disappointed. However I believe what made those films stand out is that they told the story from a different perspective, or offered a spin on the original storyline. Hopefully Cinderella follows in these footsteps - it'll be interesting to see what they come up with.

text: I think the movie trailer for "Cinderella" is nice. I admit it, I'm an emotional sap many times, & I can tear up easily when something emotionally moves me. Already hearing the memorable lines, "Where there is kindness there is goodness, where there is goodness there is magic" & the parts where Cinderella's Mom tells her that her daughter has more kindness in her little finger than most people have in their whole bodies, & for her to always remember to have kindness & courage, yeah, I got misty eyed, there. :-) I did like "Maleficent". I need to buy that DVD soon. But yeah, I'm liking the live action Disney films. I did like the "Oz", "Alice in Wonderland" films. And I heard from others that there were will be "Beauty & the Beast", "The Jungle Book" - even though there is "Jungle Book" film already out there with Jason Scott Lee, "The Little Mermaid", & "Dumbo". There are two different versions of live action "Snow White".  Regarding the Cinderella story, there are some decent films out there with live human actors playing Cinderella role - "Ever After" with Drew Barrymore - I think that was my favorite "Cinderella" movie because Drew Barrymore's character was an empowered, strong, able to save other people & fend for herself Cinderella & there are the "A Cinderella Story" movies - three of them - with Hilary Duff, Selena Gomez, & Lucy Hale playing the leads in each of those three films. Back to this "Cinderella" film - I think it will be good to see Lily James (I like watching her on "Downton Abbey" TV series, Cate Blanchett, & Helena Bonham Carter. I would like to see Disney make their own live human versions of "Pocahontas" & "Mulan".

text: I actively try not to be cynical about movies and Hollywood, but this, with the rest of Disney's fairytale remakes (Alice, Oz, and Maleficent) are pushing me too far. The original film adaptation is already one of my least favorite of Disney's animated features, so at least this won't ruin any classics for me (unlike Oz the Great and Powerful, although that one was not adapting a Disney feature). But why would they release this so soon after Into the Woods (which also has Cinderella) anyway? If that film is a success it will make this one seem even more redundant than it already is!  If I need to see Cinderella on the big screen, I'll stick with Into the Woods, at least that movie has Stephen Sondheim. And what is Robb Stark doing in this bullsh*t?!

text: Some people are saying they want Cinderella to have an edge like Malificent, have it be dark and twisted. But that's not what Cinderella is. Cinderella is a gorgeous story about a girl's strength to keep going despite how she's treated. Some may protest that it's just another romantic disney movie but I like romance every now and again. Not every live action disney film has to be intense. The casting looks perfect, the setting is beautiful, the music sounds phenomenal. It's a very marmite movie. You either love it with a burning passion or hate it. At least from what I've gathered from the comments. It's defiantly not everyone's cup of tea, and you're perfectly within your rights to dislike the trailer and not see the film, but I for one can't wait to see this movie.

text: Cinderella came out as a disney movie in 1950. It was one of the most popular youngs girl movies for forty years, straight through to the 90's. Now... cinderella has been replaced by "frozen" "tangled" aNd "brave". All movies about female potential and strength. So... in my opinion... i think that this movie is being rereleased, because the girls who grew up watching cinderella are now mothers themselves, but theres a more mature component to it because its not a cartoon, and im sure there will be much more female strength in this movie than just crying because you dont have a prince. So.... in other words... not only will little girls want to see it, but the girls mothers, and sad lonely single women will want to go see it too, meaning if you were a girl born between 1950-now, youll be a potential viewer. Wanna know what that means?... MONEY.
